with summations including all elements. This simple rule for assembly is very convenient because as soon as a coefï¬cient for a particular element is found it can be put immediately into the appropriate âlocationâ speciï¬ed in the computer. This general assembly process can be found to be the common and fundamental feature of all ï¬nite element calculations and should be well understood by the reader. If different types of structural elements are used and are to be coupled it must be remembered that at any given node the rules of matrix summation permit this to be done only if these are of identical size. The individual submatrices to be added have therefore to be built up of the same number of individual components of force or displacement.

1.4 The boundary conditions
The system of equations resulting from Eq. (1.9) can be solved once the prescribed support displacements have been substituted. In the example of Fig. 1.1, where both components of displacement of nodes 1 and 6 are zero, this will mean the substitution of u1 = u6 = 0 0

which is equivalent to reducing the number of equilibrium equations (in this instance 12) by deleting the ï¬rst and last pairs and thus reducing the total number of unknown displacement

Electrical and fluid networks

7

components to eight. It is, nevertheless, often convenient to assemble the equation according to relation (1.9) so as to include all the nodes. Clearly, without substitution of a minimum number of prescribed displacements to prevent rigid body movements of the structure, it is impossible to solve this system, because the displacements cannot be uniquely determined by the forces in such a situation. This physically obvious fact will be interpreted mathematically as the matrix K being singular, i.e., not possessing an inverse. The prescription of appropriate displacements after the assembly stage will permit a unique solution to be obtained by deleting appropriate rows and columns of the various matrices. If all the equations of a system are assembled, their form is K11 u1 + K12 u2 + Â· Â· Â· + f1 = 0 K21 u1 + K22 u2 + Â· Â· Â· + f2 = 0 etc. Â¯ and it will be noted that if any displacement, such as u1 = u1 , is prescribed then the total âforceâ f1 cannot be simultaneously speciï¬ed and remains unknown. The ï¬rst equaÂ¯ tion could then be deleted and substitution of known values u1 made in the remaining equations. When all the boundary conditions are inserted the equations of the system can be solved for the unknown nodal displacements and the internal forces in each element obtained. (1.11)

1.5 Electrical and fluid networks
