Assuming that properties are found in global coordinates we can enter each âstiffnessâ or âforceâ component in its position of the global matrix as shown in Fig. 1.3(b). Each shaded square represents a single coefï¬cient or a submatrix of type Kab if more than one quantity is being considered at the nodes. Here the separate contribution of each element is shown and the reader can verify the position of the coefï¬cients. Note that the various types of âelementsâ considered here present no difï¬culty in speciï¬cation. (All âforcesâ, including nodal ones, are here associated with elements for simplicity.) The second step is the assembly of the ï¬nal equations of the type given by Eq. (1.9). This is accomplished according to the rule of Eq. (1.10) by simple addition of all numbers in the appropriate space of the global matrix. The result is shown in Fig. 1.3(c) where the non-zero coefï¬cients are indicated by shading. If the matrices are symmetric only the half above the diagonal shown needs, in fact, to be found. All the non-zero coefï¬cients are conï¬ned within a band or proï¬le which can be calculated a priori for the nodal connections. Thus in computer programs only the storage of the elements within the proï¬le (or sparse structure) is necessary, as shown in Fig. 1.3(c). Indeed, if K is symmetric only the upper (or lower) half need be stored. The third step is the insertion of prescribed boundary conditions into the ï¬nal assembled matrix, as discussed in Sec. 1.3. This is followed by the ï¬nal step. The ï¬nal step solves the resulting equation system. Here many different methods can be employed, some of which are summarized in Appendix C. The general subject of equation solving, though extremely important, is in general beyond the scope of this book. The ï¬nal step discussed above can be followed by substitution to obtain stresses, currents, or other desired output quantities. All operations involved in structural or other network analysis are thus of an extremely simple and repetitive kind. We can now deï¬ne the standard discrete system as one in which such conditions prevail.

1.7 The standard discrete system
In the standard discrete system, whether it is structural or of any other kind, we ï¬nd that: 1. A set of discrete parameters, say ua , can be identiï¬ed which describes simultaneously the behaviour of each element, e, and of the whole system. We shall call these the system parameters.

