2.2.3 Stresses
In general, the material within the element boundaries may be subjected to initial strains such as those due to temperature changes, shrinkage, crystal growth, and so on. If such strains are denoted by Îµ0 then the stresses will be caused by the difference between the actual and initial strains. In addition it is convenient to assume that at the outset of the analysis the body is stressed by some known system of initial residual stresses Ï 0 which, for instance, could be measured, but the prediction of which is impossible without the full knowledge of the materialâs history. These stresses can simply be added on to the general deï¬nition. Thus, assuming linear elastic behaviour, the relationship between stresses and strains will be linear and of the form Ï = D(Îµ â Îµ0 ) + Ï 0 (2.16) where D is an elasticity matrix containing the appropriate material properties. Again for the particular case of plane stress three components of stress corresponding to the strains already deï¬ned have to be considered. These are, in familiar notation, â§ â« â¨ Ïx â¬ Ï = Ïy â© â­ Ïxy and for an isotropic material the D matrix may be simply obtained from the usual stressâ strain relationship6 Îµx â Îµx0 = Îµy â Îµy0 Î³xy â Î³xy0 1 Î½ (Ïx â Ïx0 ) â (Ïy â Ïy0 ) E E Î½ 1 = â (Ïx â Ïx0 ) + (Ïy â Ïy0 ) E E 2(1 + Î½) = (Ïxy â Ïxy0 ) E

