Put in other words, we require that the terms integrated in Eq. (2.42) be ï¬nite. These terms arise from the shape functions Na used in deï¬ning the displacement u [by Eq. (2.35)] and its derivatives associated with the deï¬nition of strain [viz. Eq. (2.14)]. If, for instance, the âstrainsâ are deï¬ned by ï¬rst derivatives of the functions N, the displacements must be continuous. In Fig. 2.7 we see how ï¬rst derivatives of continuous functions may involve a âjumpâ but are still ï¬nite, while second derivatives may become inï¬nite. Such functions we call C0 continuous. In some problems the âstrainâ in a generalized sense may be deï¬ned by second derivatives. In such cases we shall obviously require that both the function N and its slope (ï¬rst derivative) be continuous. Such functions are more difï¬cult to derive but are used in the analysis of thin plate and shell problems (e.g., see volume on solid mechanics7 ). The continuity involved now is called C1 .

