This last example is typical of a so-called mixed formulation. In such problems the number of dependent unknowns can always be reduced in the governing equations by suitable algebraic operation, still leaving a solvable problem [e.g., obtaining Eq. (3.8) from (3.10) by eliminating qx and qy ]. If this cannot be done [viz. Eq.(3.8)] we have an irreducible formulation. Problems of mixed form present certain complexities in their solution which we shall discuss in Chapter 11. In Chapter 7 we shall return to detailed examples of the ï¬rst problem and other examples will be introduced throughout the book. The above three sets of problems will, however, be useful in their full form or reduced to one dimension (by suppressing the y variable) to illustrate the various approaches used in this chapter.

