as non-square integrable. Such a function is said to be C0 continuous. In a similar way it is easy to see that if nth-order derivatives occur in any term of A or B then the function has to be such that its n â 1 derivatives are continuous (Cnâ1 continuity). On many occasions it is possible to perform an integration by parts on Eq. (3.13) and replace it by an alternative statement of the form C(v)T D(u)d + E(Â¯ )T F (u)d = 0 v (3.14)

In this the operators C to F usually contain lower order derivatives than those occurring in operators A or B. Now a lower order of continuity is required in the choice of the u Â¯ function at a price of higher continuity for v and v. The statement (3.14) is now more âpermissiveâ than the original problem posed by Eq. (3.1), (3.2), or (3.13) and is called a weak form of these equations. It is a somewhat surprising fact that often this weak form is more realistic physically than the original differential equation which implied an excessive âsmoothnessâ of the true solution. Integral statements of the form of (3.13) and (3.14) will form the basis of ï¬nite element approximations, and we shall discuss them later in fuller detail. Before doing so we shall apply the new formulation to an example. Example 3.4: Weak form of the heat conduction equation â forced and natural boundary conditions. Consider now the integral form of Eq. (3.8). We can write the statement (3.13) as v â âÏ â k âx âx â â âÏ k ây ây + Q dx dy +
