Ë all independent coordinates of the problem and that u was simply a set of constants. The ï¬nal approximation equations were thus always of an algebraic form, from which a unique set of parameters could be determined. In some problems it is convenient to proceed differently. Thus, for instance, if the Ë independent variables are x, y and z we could allow the parameters u to be functions of z and do the approximate expansion only in the domain of x, y, say Â¯ . Thus, in place of Eq. (3.3) we would have Ë u = N(x, y) u(z) (3.50) Ë Clearly the derivatives of u with respect to z will remain in the ï¬nal discretization and the result will be a set of ordinary differential equations with z as the independent variable. In linear problems such a set will have the appearance Ë Ë Ë K u + Cu + Â· Â· Â· + f = 0 (3.51)

Ë Ë Ë where u â¡ du/dz, etc. Such a partial discretization can obviously be used in different ways, but is particularly useful when the domain Â¯ is not dependent on z, i.e., when the problem is prismatic. In such a case the coefï¬cient matrices of the ordinary differential equations, (3.51), are independent of z and the solution of the system can frequently be carried out efï¬ciently by standard analytical methods. This type of partial discretization has been applied extensively by Kantorovich13 and is frequently known by his name. Semi-analytical treatments are presented in reference 14 for prismatic solids where the ï¬nal solution is obtained in terms of Fourier (or other) series. However, the most frequently encountered âprismaticâ problem is one involving the time variable, where the space domain Â¯ is not subject to change. We shall address such problems in Chapter 16 of this volume. It is convenient by way of illustration to consider here heat conduction in a two-dimensional equation in its transient state. This is obtained from Eq. (3.8) by addition of the heat storage term c(âÏ/ât), where c is the speciï¬c heat per unit volume. We now have a problem posed in a domain (x, y, t) in which the following equation holds: A(Ï) â¡ â â âÏ k âx âx â â âÏ k ây ây +Q+c âÏ =0 ât (3.52)

