3.10 Maximum, minimum, or a saddle point?
In discussing variational principles so far we have assumed simply that at the solution point Î´ = 0, that is the functional is stationary. It is often desirable to know whether is at a maximum, minimum, or simply at a âsaddle pointâ. If a maximum or a minimum is involved, then the approximation to will always be âboundedâ, i.e., will provide approximate values of which are either smaller or larger than the correct ones.â  The bound in itself may be of practical signiï¬cance in some problems. When, in elementary calculus, we consider a stationary point of a function of one variable u, we investigate the rate of change of d with du and write d(d ) = d â du âu = â2 (du)2 âu2 (3.93)

