3.11.2 Identification of Lagrange multipliers. Forced boundary conditions and modified variational principles
Although the Lagrange multipliers were introduced as a mathematical concept necessary for the enforcement of certain external constraints required to satisfy the original variational principle, we shall ï¬nd that in many situations they can be identiï¬ed with certain physical quantities of importance to the original mathematical model. Such an identiï¬cation will follow immediately from the deï¬nition of the variational principle established in Eq. (3.96) and through the ï¬rst of the Euler equations in (3.105) corresponding to it. The variation Î´ Â¯ , written in Eq. (3.97), supplies through its third term the constraint equation. The ï¬rst two terms can always be rewritten as Î´C(u)T Î» d or Î´E(u)T Î» d + Î´uT B(u) d = 0 (3.115b) This supplies the identiï¬cation of Î». In the literature of variational calculation such identiï¬cation arises frequently and the reader is referred to the excellent text by Washizu25 for numerous examples. Example 3.12: Identiï¬cation of Lagrange multiplier for boundary condition. Here we shall introduce this identiï¬cation by means of the example considered in Sec. 3.8.1. As we have noted, the variational principle of Eq. (3.71) established the governing equation and the natural boundary conditions of the heat conduction problem providing the forced boundary condition Â¯ E(Ï) = Ï â Ï = 0 (3.116) was satisï¬ed on Ï in the choice of the trial function for Ï. The above forced boundary condition can, however, be considered as a constraint on the original problem. We can write the constrained variational principle as Â¯ = where is given by Eq. (3.71). Performing the variation we have Î´Â¯ =Î´ Î´ +
